[Counterexample to Proposition 5 from \cite{AM22}]
	Let $d\ge 4$. Then there is a set $P=\{p_0,\dots,p_{d+2}\}$ of points in $\mathbb R^d$ in general position such that each pair of distinct points in $P$ defines a unique distance and the order that $P$ induces on $\binom{[d+3]}{2}$ satisfies the following conditions:
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item for any $(i, j)\in \binom{[d]}{2}$ and $(k, l) \in \binom{[d+3]}{2} \setminus \binom{[d]}{2}$ we have $(k, l) < (i, j)$, and
		\item for any $(i, j)\in [d]\times \{d,d+1,d+2\}$ and $(k, l) \in \binom{[d+3]}{2}\setminus([d]\times \{d,d+1,d+2\})$ we have $(i, j) < (k, l)$.
	\end{enumerate}

